sentences: Bernard William Jewry (27 September 1942 – 23 October 2014), known professionally as Shane Fenton and later as Alvin Stardust, was an English rock singer and stage actor.
Bernard William Jewry was born 27 September 1942 in Muswell Hill, then in Middlesex (now in north London).

Having moved at a young age to Mansfield, Nottinghamshire, where his mother ran a boarding house frequented by musicians and entertainers appearing locally, Jewry attended the Southwell Minster Collegiate Grammar School (now Southwell Minster School) in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, near Newark-on-Trent, as a boarder.
The combo had a few hits in the UK Singles Chart: "I'm A Moody Guy", "Walk Away", "It's All Over Now" and their biggest hit, "Cindy's Birthday".
In total, he amassed seven Top Ten entries, in a chart span lasting almost 25 years.
Alvin Stardust was a guest act on the Morecambe & Wise Christmas Show in 1981.
"So Near To Christmas" was a minor hit, No. 29, in the same year.
That year he also performed at Windsor Castle as a lead in the Lloyd Webber–Rice musical Cricket.
In 1989, he also hosted his own Sunday morning children's TV series on ITV called It's Stardust.
In 1995, he joined the cast of the soap opera, Hollyoaks, playing the character Greg Andersen from October 1995 to July 1996.
Their daughter, Sophie Jewry, was critically injured at the age of two months after she fell down a set of stairs and suffered a severe fracture of the skull; she later recovered from her injuries.
His death came weeks before he was due to release his first album for 30 years, and six days after what became his last show at the Regal Cinema, Evesham.
He had been diagnosed with prostate cancer 18 months earlier, which later metastasised.
